column1: Question
You regularly make new friends.
You feel comfortable just walking up to someone you find interesting and striking up a conversation.
You enjoy participating in group activities.
You usually prefer to be around others rather than on your own.
After a long and exhausting week, a lively social event is just what you need.
In your social circle, you are often the one who contacts your friends and initiates activities.
You feel more drawn to places with busy, bustling atmospheres than quiet, intimate places.
It doesn't take long to get involved in the social activities of your new workplace.
You don't mind being the center of attention.
Your energy is multiplied if you have spent time with a group.
At social events, you rarely try to introduce yourself to new people and mostly talk to the ones you already know.
You avoid leadership roles in group settings.
You tend to avoid drawing attention to yourself.
You avoid making phone calls.
You are a relatively quiet and reserved person.
A quality book or video game is often better than a social event.
Usually, you don't initiate conversations.
You have difficulty relaxing when speaking in front of many people.
If the room is crowded, you stay close to the walls and avoid the center.
You would love a job that requires you to work alone most of the time.
You spend a lot of your free time exploring various random topics that pique your interest.
You like books and movies that make you come up with your own interpretation of the ending.
You are interested in so many things that you find it difficult to choose what to try next.
You enjoy watching people argue.
You enjoy going to art museums.
You have always been fascinated by the question of what, if anything, happens after death.
You are very intrigued by things labeled as controversial.
You often spend time exploring ideas that are unrealistic and unworkable, but also intriguing.
You often reflect on the reasons for human existence.
Your mind is constantly full of ideas and plans to explore.
You are not too interested in discussing various interpretations and analyses of creative works.
You are definitely not an artistic type of person.
You become bored or lose interest when the discussion gets highly theoretical.
You rarely contemplate the reasons for human existence or the meaning of life.
Your dreams tend to focus on the real world and its events.
You see your mind as more practical than creative.
Generally, you rely more on your experience than your imagination.
You rarely take action out of curiosity.
You are rarely distracted by your dreams and thoughts.
You believe that pondering abstract philosophical questions is a waste of time.
Seeing other people cry can easily make you feel like you want to cry too.
You are very sentimental.
Your happiness comes more from helping others accomplish things than your own accomplishments.
You find it easy to empathize with a person whose experiences are very different from yours.
You take great care not to make people look bad, even when it is completely their fault.
You know at first glance how someone is feeling.
You would pass along a good opportunity if you thought someone else needed it more.
Winning a debate is less important to you than knowing that no one is upset.
You often feel like you have to justify yourself to your peers.
You would rather see your child become nice than smart, as a parent.
You rarely worry about the consequences of your actions on your peers.
If you had a business, you would find it difficult to fire loyal employees who are not meeting their goals.
If your friends are really sad about a situation, you are more likely to offer emotional support than to suggest solutions to the problem.
You are more inclined to follow your head than your heart.
You feel superior to others.
You don't let others influence your actions.
Logic is usually more important than feelings when it comes to making important decisions.
You think the world would be a better place if people relied more on rationality and less on their feelings.
In a discussion, the truth must come before anyone's sensitivities.
You believe that it is more rewarding to be appreciated by others than to be powerful.
You have difficulty empathizing with the feelings of others.
In teamwork, it is more important to be right than to be cooperative.
You lose patience with people who are not as efficient as you.
You often have a hard time understanding other people's feelings.
You often make a backup plan for a backup plan.
You prefer to completely finish one project before starting another.
You like to use organizing tools like schedules and lists.
You prefer to do your chores before allowing yourself to relax.
You like to have a to-do list for each day.
If your plans are interrupted, your top priority is to get back on track as soon as possible.
You complete things methodically without skipping over any steps.
You try to answer your emails as soon as possible and can't stand having an unorganized mailbox.
For you, being organized is more important than being flexible.
Your living environment is quite orderly, at work and at home.
Your travel itineraries are usually planned in advance.
Being able to develop a plan and stick to it is the most important part of every project.
You usually prefer just doing what you feel like at any given moment instead of planning a particular daily routine.
You often end up doing things at the last possible moment.
You usually postpone finalizing decisions for as long as possible.
You are more of a natural improviser than a meticulous planner.
You would rather improvise than spend time on building a detailed plan.
It is more important to keep a choice of possibilities open than to have a list of things to do.
You frequently lose your things.
You tend to put everything off until there is not enough time left to do everything.
You struggle with deadlines.
Your personal work style is closer to spontaneous bursts of energy than organized and consistent efforts.
You usually stay calm, even under a lot of pressure.
You rarely second-guess the choices that you have made.
You rarely feel insecure.
You feel confident that things will work out for you.
People can rarely upset you.
You consider yourself to be very emotionally stable.
Even a small mistake can cause you to doubt your overall abilities and knowledge.
You rarely worry about whether you make a good impression on people you meet.
You are prone to worrying that things will take a turn for the worse.
You often feel overwhelmed.
Your mood can change very quickly.
You often spend a lot of time trying to understand views that are very different from your own.
You are still bothered by mistakes that you made a long time ago.
Your emotions control you more than you control them.
You feel very anxious in stressful situations.
If someone doesn't respond quickly to your email, you worry and wonder if you said something wrong.
When someone thinks highly of you, you wonder how long it will take them to feel disappointed in you.
